---
import GuideLayout from "../../layouts/GuideLayout.astro";

const title = "Estimating log costs (ingestion and retention)";
const description =
  "A practical guide to modeling log bills: ingestion vs retention, steady state, and volume reduction strategies.";
---
<GuideLayout title={title} description={description} canonicalPath="/guides/log-costs" lastUpdated="2026-01-06">
  <p class="muted">
    Most log platforms charge for <strong>ingestion</strong> (GB ingested) and for <strong>retention</strong> (stored
    data). If your bill surprised you, it’s usually because volume or retention drifted upward.
  </p>

  <h2>1) Separate ingestion from storage</h2>
  <ul>
    <li><strong>Ingestion</strong>: GB/day × price per GB.</li>
    <li><strong>Retention storage</strong>: roughly GB/day × retention days (steady state) × $/GB-month.</li>
  </ul>

  <h2>2) Use a steady-state model for retention</h2>
  <p>
    After you’ve been logging longer than your retention window, the dataset size is roughly constant: the last N days.
    That’s why “GB/day × retention days” is a useful planning estimate.
  </p>

  <h2>3) The knobs that usually matter most</h2>
  <ul>
    <li>Drop or sample high-volume debug logs.</li>
    <li>Shorten hot retention; archive cold data to object storage.</li>
    <li>Index selectively (store everything, index what you query).</li>
  </ul>

  <h2>Tools</h2>
  <ul>
    <li><a href="/calculators/log-ingestion-cost-calculator/">Log ingestion cost calculator</a></li>
    <li><a href="/calculators/log-retention-storage-cost-calculator/">Log retention storage cost calculator</a></li>
  </ul>
</GuideLayout>
